english:
  title: A Preface on Presenting a Title to Monk Igu
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Among the monks of Jogye Temple, there is one called Jonghae. When I inquired about the origin of his name, I learned that it was grounded in Buddhist teaching, and it happened to accord with a passage from the Summer Annals that speaks of "all waters returning to the sea." Yet when he came to request a title from me, he did not present this classical allusion. Instead, he explained the reason his name was chosen: it derives from the mirror's reflection of all things, responding to their kind without bias or preference.

    The ocean, as a thing among heaven and earth, has no equal. Thus when scholars speak of water, they point to the earth and say, "This is what water bears." But earth, pairing with heaven as the greater, is said to be borne by water—so which is greater, water or heaven? How can we measure such things? Consider: when rain falls from heaven, each drop strikes another, and foam is born. Foam is surely the smallest manifestation of water. Yet if the smallest can be paired with the greatest, would not this be mere appearance? It is like the error of comparing Pengzu, who lived eight hundred years, with the child who died young—or a great roc with a quail. No, such comparison fails.

    Yet understand: whether we call it sea or foam, these are but different names. The foam returns to its sea; the sea receives its foam. Are there traces of this, or is there nothing? When the foam dissolves into unity, when there is no longer division, then not only is the principle one—the thing itself is also unchanged. Thus the Buddha-followers say: erase all marks and traces, and return to Emptiness; arrange and distribute the elements, and return to the Sea. Though the sea is vast, it never departs from its nature.

    Therefore their words speak of both "Quiescent Extinction" and "Birth and Death." The foam that appears as the sea in Quiescent Extinction—this is what is called the Buddhas. The foam that appears as the sea in Birth and Death—this is what is called sentient beings.

    Now, in which realm shall this Venerable One manifest as foam? And does he truly know whether Birth and Death and Quiescent Extinction are two or one? Should the Venerable One rest content with what he has received from his teacher, satisfied within his own mind, he may not escape recklessness. He should seek wide counsel from the great scholars of the world, and surely they will have instruction for him.

    The Venerable One's secular family name is Cao, and he is from Hoejin County in Naju. He rose through the selection examination, teaches in Jukwon Temple, and is thirty-one years of age. His teacher, the Great Preceptor Chong, was a disciple of Namsan. When we speak of a person, we must mention their lineage, so I record this as well.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Jogye Temple (Jogyesa) is one of the major temples of Korean Buddhism and was the center of Seon (Zen) Buddhism in medieval Korea.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to the Summer Annals (Xiaoshu) and 'all waters returning to the sea' alludes to the Confucian principle of all things moving toward their source, here cleverly connected to Buddhist cosmology.
  - key: ''
    value: The foam (bubbles) metaphor is used to represent individual manifestations arising from and returning to the fundamental nature—a common Buddhist teaching on the relationship between the individual and the universal.
  - key: ''
    value: Pengzu, the child who died young, and the great roc and quail are classical references to the relativity of values—comparing incomparables is the point of the allusion.
